  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "<!-- **Are you in the right place?**\r\n1. For issues or feature requests, please create an issue in this repository.\r\n2. For general technical and non-technical questions, we are happy to help you on our [Rook.io Slack](https://Rook-io.slack.com).\r\n3. Did you already search the existing open issues for anything similar? -->\r\n\r\n**Is this a bug report or feature request?**\r\n* Feature Request\r\n\r\n**What should the feature do:**\r\n[jbw976] The agent and discovery pods should support more advanced placement options, such as `nodeAffinity`, to control which nodes these pods are run on.  This could mean to not even run them at all if that's what the user desires.\r\n\r\n**What is use case behind this feature:**\r\nThe discovery daemonset  used to collect disk information is refreshed every 30 seconds  on every node.\r\nUsually the hard disk info of an stable cluster would not change frequently, so this behavior is not meaningful. Maybe it is enough that manually running a job to update disk information   before the first deployment of rook  or any hardware changes of the k8s cluster.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile currently the discovery pod could only be controlled by toleration. Usually I want to specify the nodes that need to collect disk information, not the nodes that do not need to collect information. So \r\nI think using nodeAffinity to control discovery pod is more suitable\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n<!-- Specific environment information that helps with the feature request -->\r\n",
